  <title>Week 7 Assignment</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the following derivatives. Label the rules you
        used. (12) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d}{dx} \ln (\cos x)
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d}{dx} \sin t  + \cos^2 t 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d}{dx} \sqrt[3]{13x^2 + 4}
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the following derivatives. Annotate your work and
        show sufficient steps to make the process of consecutive
        differentiation clear. (12)
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d^2}{dx^2} \frac{x^2+1}{x+1}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d^4}{dx^4} e^{9x}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d^6}{dx^6} \cos x - \sin x 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \frac{d^{100}}{dx^{100}} 2^x
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Use L'Hôpital's Rule to solve these limits. (Make sure you
        explicitly check that these limits have the appropriate type
        before using L'Hôpital's Rule.) (12) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} \frac{x^3 - 6x^2 + 9x - 4}{x^3 -
            11x^2 + 13x - 48} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} \frac{x^2 \ln x}{x^2 + 6}
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this trig identity.
        <me>
          \sin (2x) = 2 \sin x \cos x 
        </me>
        Since both sides are the same, they should have the same
        derivative. Take the derivative of both sides using
        appropriate rules and show that the result is the same (6). 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
